1
00:00:07,507 --> 00:00:08,942
WOMAN:
What do you see here?

2
00:00:08,942 --> 00:00:10,510
DAPHNE:
It's two bunnies

3
00:00:10,510 --> 00:00:14,014
clawing each other to death
over a lima bean.

4
00:00:15,448 --> 00:00:17,884
Forgive me, Dr. McCaskill,

5
00:00:17,884 --> 00:00:19,386
but this game seems rather silly.

6
00:00:19,386 --> 00:00:21,388
I understand how you
might feel that way,

7
00:00:21,388 --> 00:00:23,356
but it's helpful to me.

8
00:00:23,356 --> 00:00:24,324
Now, last one.

9
00:00:24,324 --> 00:00:26,793
It's a woman.

10
00:00:26,793 --> 00:00:28,695
Okay, then.

11
00:00:29,529 --> 00:00:33,066
She's skinning a pigeon
with a hatchet.

12
00:00:36,436 --> 00:00:38,872
Are we done now?

13
00:00:38,872 --> 00:00:41,808
I think we still
have some work to do.

14
00:00:41,808 --> 00:00:43,877
I just don't think
there's any good reason

15
00:00:43,877 --> 00:00:45,178
for me to be here.

16
00:00:45,178 --> 00:00:46,946
The judge felt differently.

17
00:00:46,946 --> 00:00:48,314
Oh, what does he know?

18
00:00:48,314 --> 00:00:50,150
Saying I need anger management.

19
00:00:50,150 --> 00:00:51,651
I'm not an angry person.

20
00:00:51,651 --> 00:00:53,420
I never have been.

21
00:00:53,420 --> 00:00:55,188
Daphne, wasn't it anger
that led you to cause

22
00:00:55,188 --> 00:00:56,556
that four-car accident?

23
00:00:56,556 --> 00:00:59,426
Oh, yes, but I was provoked
into that.

24
00:00:59,426 --> 00:01:02,228
Mm-hmm. I'm not angry anymore.

25
00:01:02,228 --> 00:01:04,030
Well, there may be a level of emotion

26
00:01:04,030 --> 00:01:05,532
you're not entirely in touch with.

27
00:01:05,532 --> 00:01:08,034
Let's talk about your life in general.

28
00:01:08,034 --> 00:01:09,502
You said you had a fiance?

29
00:01:09,502 --> 00:01:11,971
Yes, Donny.

30
00:01:11,971 --> 00:01:13,973
He's a wonderful, generous man.

31
00:01:13,973 --> 00:01:17,477
In fact, he did the sweetest
thing for me last week,

32
00:01:17,477 --> 00:01:18,978
totally out of the blue.

33
00:01:18,978 --> 00:01:21,981
PEOPLE: Surprise!

34
00:01:23,583 --> 00:01:25,285
Welcome to your shower,

35
00:01:25,285 --> 00:01:26,920
honey.

36
00:01:26,920 --> 00:01:28,254
Oh, my God, you're trembling.

37
00:01:28,254 --> 00:01:32,025
Yes, well, I'm
absolutely blown away.

38
00:01:32,025 --> 00:01:33,259
Oh, come on Daphne.
You were on to us.

39
00:01:33,259 --> 00:01:34,828
No, really.

40
00:01:34,828 --> 00:01:37,197
You had me completely fooled.

41
00:01:37,197 --> 00:01:40,066
We may have an even bigger
surprise for you later on.

42
00:01:40,066 --> 00:01:42,001
Oh? Yes, but first things first.

43
00:01:42,001 --> 00:01:44,404
Let's get you some champagne.

44
00:01:44,404 --> 00:01:46,973
DAPHNE: I'm not usually much
for surprise parties,

45
00:01:46,973 --> 00:01:49,476
but I could see how much trouble
Donny went to.

46
00:01:49,476 --> 00:01:52,479
He invited all my friends,
made the food.

47
00:01:52,479 --> 00:01:54,481
He even planned some games.

48
00:01:54,481 --> 00:01:57,484
We played this one game
where everyone's in groups,

49
00:01:57,484 --> 00:01:59,486
then each group dresses one person

50
00:01:59,486 --> 00:02:01,488
in a bridal gown made out of toilet paper.

51
00:02:01,488 --> 00:02:03,490
Can't remember what it's called.

52
00:02:03,490 --> 00:02:05,992
"Toilet Paper Bridal Gown."

53
00:02:05,992 --> 00:02:08,495
Yes, that's it. Have you played?

54
00:02:08,495 --> 00:02:10,997
I'm familiar with it.

55
00:02:10,997 --> 00:02:12,465
Then, you know, as the bride,

56
00:02:12,465 --> 00:02:15,001
I had to judge which group made
the best dress

57
00:02:15,502 --> 00:02:17,003
while another woman
was in charge of...

58
00:02:17,003 --> 00:02:18,505
(whistle blows)

59
00:02:18,505 --> 00:02:21,975
Time! Stop right now
or be disqualified!

60
00:02:21,975 --> 00:02:24,511
Designers, present your brides.

61
00:02:24,511 --> 00:02:25,778
Team A.

62
00:02:25,778 --> 00:02:28,414
Ta-da!

63
00:02:28,414 --> 00:02:30,817
Oh, very nice, Donny.

64
00:02:30,817 --> 00:02:32,552
Team B.

65
00:02:32,552 --> 00:02:34,354
We're not finished yet.

66
00:02:34,354 --> 00:02:35,355
You shouldn't have spent

67
00:02:35,355 --> 00:02:37,857
so much time with the sketches.

68
00:02:37,857 --> 00:02:39,125
MEL: Team C.

69
00:02:39,125 --> 00:02:40,860
Where's Team C?
Team C, time!

70
00:02:40,860 --> 00:02:45,732
(humming "Bridal March")

71
00:02:47,667 --> 00:02:49,002
You'll notice

72
00:02:49,002 --> 00:02:51,337
that I used the quilted variety
for the bodice

73
00:02:51,337 --> 00:02:53,206
and the edging on the veil.

74
00:02:53,206 --> 00:02:56,109
Well, you all look fantastic,

75
00:02:56,109 --> 00:02:58,845
but I think we have a winner--
Team C.

76
00:02:58,845 --> 00:03:02,549
(Team C cheering)

77
00:03:02,549 --> 00:03:04,417
Oh, Donny, I'm sorry.

78
00:03:04,417 --> 00:03:05,919
Holly, it's not your fault.

79
00:03:05,919 --> 00:03:09,322
I should have been more radiant.

80
00:03:09,322 --> 00:03:10,757
Daphne, listen, if
there happens to be

81
00:03:10,757 --> 00:03:12,692
another game that we play, do you
think you could arrange for me

82
00:03:12,692 --> 00:03:14,661
to be on the same team as your friend
Holly there?

83
00:03:15,161 --> 00:03:16,162
Oh, developed a little crush, have we?

84
00:03:16,162 --> 00:03:17,564
As a matter of fact, I have.

85
00:03:17,564 --> 00:03:18,965
It's just that I haven't
had much of a chance

86
00:03:18,965 --> 00:03:19,966
to get to speak with her at all.

87
00:03:20,466 --> 00:03:21,801
Well, I'll do what I can,

88
00:03:21,801 --> 00:03:23,102
but I'm not really in charge here.

89
00:03:23,102 --> 00:03:24,604
(blows whistle)

90
00:03:24,604 --> 00:03:26,105
All right, people.

91
00:03:26,105 --> 00:03:27,640
Next game, bridal charades.

92
00:03:27,640 --> 00:03:29,642
(guests moaning and cheering)
(doorbell ringing)

93
00:03:29,642 --> 00:03:31,077
Oh, oh!

94
00:03:31,077 --> 00:03:32,445
Roz, you know, someday
you're going to make

95
00:03:33,012 --> 00:03:34,013
a beautiful bride.

96
00:03:34,013 --> 00:03:36,849
'Course, your dress won't be made out
of toilet paper.

97
00:03:36,849 --> 00:03:38,084
Or be white.

98
00:03:38,084 --> 00:03:40,019
DONNY: Everybody.

99
00:03:40,019 --> 00:03:41,521
Daphne...

100
00:03:41,521 --> 00:03:44,290
your big surprise has arrived.

101
00:03:44,290 --> 00:03:46,059
Now, this is someone that I know

102
00:03:46,059 --> 00:03:47,894
that you are dying to see.

103
00:03:47,894 --> 00:03:49,562
Your parents?

104
00:03:49,562 --> 00:03:51,231
No, not till next week.

105
00:03:51,231 --> 00:03:52,966
My mother?

106
00:03:52,966 --> 00:03:54,234
No, someone good.

107
00:03:55,902 --> 00:03:56,736
My brother?

108
00:03:56,736 --> 00:03:58,571
Your favorite brother.

109
00:03:58,571 --> 00:04:00,240
Oh...

110
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,008
Yay! Stephen!

111
00:04:02,008 --> 00:04:03,876
Ste... No.

112
00:04:04,777 --> 00:04:06,179
Billy.

113
00:04:06,179 --> 00:04:07,113
Um...

114
00:04:07,113 --> 00:04:08,581
DAPHNE: Michael?
Well...

115
00:04:08,581 --> 00:04:09,949
Nigel? David?

116
00:04:09,949 --> 00:04:11,284
MAN: Hello.

117
00:04:11,284 --> 00:04:12,952
Thirsty man waiting out here.

118
00:04:14,287 --> 00:04:15,121
Simon.

119
00:04:16,456 --> 00:04:17,457
Hello.

120
00:04:17,457 --> 00:04:19,959
Daphne... come here.

121
00:04:19,959 --> 00:04:22,262
Ah! I got you again!

122
00:04:23,930 --> 00:04:25,698
Everyone,

123
00:04:25,698 --> 00:04:27,100
this is my brother, Simon.

124
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:28,534
ALL: Hi, Simon.

125
00:04:28,534 --> 00:04:30,870
Ah, Stilts, aren't you a sight?

126
00:04:30,870 --> 00:04:32,205
"Stilts"?

127
00:04:32,205 --> 00:04:34,107
Growing up, I was a
bit tall for my age.

128
00:04:34,107 --> 00:04:36,676
Giant, like she was
on stilts.

129
00:04:36,676 --> 00:04:38,177
They follow you, Simon.

130
00:04:38,177 --> 00:04:39,579
Yeah, right.

131
00:04:39,579 --> 00:04:41,381
Well, it's nice to meet you all,

132
00:04:41,381 --> 00:04:43,583
especially whichever one's
the bartender.

133
00:04:43,583 --> 00:04:45,785
Oh, that would be me.

134
00:04:45,785 --> 00:04:48,154
Oh, and a pretty
little bartender you are.

135
00:04:48,154 --> 00:04:49,489
Right this way.

136
00:04:49,489 --> 00:04:50,456
After you.

137
00:04:50,456 --> 00:04:51,958
Oh.

138
00:04:51,958 --> 00:04:54,460
I'd rather walk behind you, anyway.

139
00:04:54,460 --> 00:04:55,962
I just love your accent.

140
00:04:55,962 --> 00:04:57,463
It's so sophisticated.

141
00:04:57,463 --> 00:05:00,833
Oh, right.

142
00:05:04,871 --> 00:05:07,440
DONNY: Oh, boy, I really screwed up,
didn't I?

143
00:05:07,874 --> 00:05:09,442
Isn't Stephen the
favorite brother?

144
00:05:09,942 --> 00:05:10,843
Yes. Even I knew that,

145
00:05:10,843 --> 00:05:12,512
and I barely listen to her.

146
00:05:12,512 --> 00:05:13,813
I know, I know, I know.

147
00:05:13,813 --> 00:05:14,814
I got the names mixed up,

148
00:05:14,814 --> 00:05:16,316
but you have mentioned Simon, too.

149
00:05:16,316 --> 00:05:17,817
Yeah, as a freeloader who just sits

150
00:05:17,817 --> 00:05:19,252
around the house drinking beer all day.

151
00:05:19,252 --> 00:05:20,586
Well, that's a lot of people.

152
00:05:20,586 --> 00:05:21,988
You're retired.

153
00:05:24,390 --> 00:05:26,859
You have such a dirty mind.

154
00:05:26,859 --> 00:05:28,361
And that would be

155
00:05:28,361 --> 00:05:31,230
a terrible thing to waste.

156
00:05:32,098 --> 00:05:33,599
Uh, Simon...

157
00:05:33,599 --> 00:05:35,034
Yeah, right.

158
00:05:35,034 --> 00:05:36,536
This is Dr. Frasier Crane

159
00:05:36,536 --> 00:05:37,537
and his father, Martin.

160
00:05:37,537 --> 00:05:39,038
Oh, yeah. Pleasure to meet you.

161
00:05:39,038 --> 00:05:40,073
Simon, how are you?

162
00:05:40,073 --> 00:05:41,074
Pleasure to meet you.

163
00:05:41,074 --> 00:05:42,575
These are the people I work for.

164
00:05:42,575 --> 00:05:44,577
And you've met my fiance, Donny.

165
00:05:44,577 --> 00:05:46,512
Oh, thanks for flying me over.

166
00:05:46,512 --> 00:05:47,447
Yeah, about that...

167
00:05:47,447 --> 00:05:49,382
Didn't it seem unusual to you

168
00:05:49,382 --> 00:05:50,950
when he called you
my favorite brother?

169
00:05:50,950 --> 00:05:53,453
Mm. Now that you mention it,

170
00:05:53,453 --> 00:05:55,722
it did strike my ear as a bit odd,

171
00:05:55,722 --> 00:05:57,490
you being so partial to Stephen.

172
00:05:57,490 --> 00:05:58,991
But then I thought,

173
00:05:58,991 --> 00:06:00,993
women change their minds
all the time.

174
00:06:00,993 --> 00:06:03,396
Brothers fall in and out of favor.

175
00:06:03,396 --> 00:06:05,565
Maybe it's my turn.

176
00:06:05,565 --> 00:06:06,833
And a good thing, too,

177
00:06:06,833 --> 00:06:08,835
as it was an especially good time

178
00:06:08,835 --> 00:06:11,304
for me to get out of England.

179
00:06:13,573 --> 00:06:16,709
God, he talks just like a prince.

180
00:06:18,878 --> 00:06:21,647
So, uh, Simon,

181
00:06:21,647 --> 00:06:23,583
where are you staying?
Thanks, mate.

182
00:06:23,583 --> 00:06:25,084
Uh, Donny here says

183
00:06:25,084 --> 00:06:26,919
that Frasier's offered to put me up.

184
00:06:26,919 --> 00:06:27,787
Yes, well, I mean, when he told me

185
00:06:27,787 --> 00:06:29,589
that he was inviting
Daphne's favorite brother,

186
00:06:29,589 --> 00:06:31,290
I-I didn't hesitate.

187
00:06:31,290 --> 00:06:32,158
'Course, well, the sad truth is,

188
00:06:32,158 --> 00:06:33,559
we don't really have a bed for you.

189
00:06:33,559 --> 00:06:35,862
Oh, a couch will suit me just fine.

190
00:06:35,862 --> 00:06:38,264
Well, I mean, you wouldn't
really be comfortable there

191
00:06:38,264 --> 00:06:39,599
for more than a day or two.

192
00:06:39,599 --> 00:06:40,933
Oh, don't worry about that.

193
00:06:40,933 --> 00:06:42,935
I once slept on a couch
for three months

194
00:06:42,935 --> 00:06:45,271
before I even realized
it pulled out.

195
00:06:47,473 --> 00:06:49,308
The main thing is that I spend

196
00:06:49,308 --> 00:06:51,811
as much time as possible
with my baby sister!

197
00:06:52,311 --> 00:06:54,313
Oh! Simon, look what you did!

198
00:06:54,814 --> 00:06:56,816
It was my absolute favorite dress--

199
00:06:56,816 --> 00:06:58,818
one I save for special occasions.

200
00:06:58,818 --> 00:07:00,820
He wasn't in the door
five minutes

201
00:07:00,820 --> 00:07:01,821
before he ruined it.

202
00:07:01,821 --> 00:07:03,823
And yet you still
felt responsible

203
00:07:03,823 --> 00:07:05,324
for putting him up.

204
00:07:05,324 --> 00:07:06,826
I didn't have much choice.

205
00:07:06,826 --> 00:07:07,827
If I turned him out,

206
00:07:07,827 --> 00:07:09,662
I'd never hear the end
of it from Mum.

207
00:07:09,662 --> 00:07:11,497
I'm hearing that your relatives
are a source

208
00:07:11,497 --> 00:07:13,266
of some anger for you.

209
00:07:13,266 --> 00:07:15,435
So? Aren't yours?

210
00:07:15,435 --> 00:07:17,837
Well, they might be if I still talked
to any of them.

211
00:07:21,207 --> 00:07:23,509
Anyway, uh...

212
00:07:23,509 --> 00:07:25,745
I can see how

213
00:07:25,745 --> 00:07:27,713
your brother's presence
was adding stress,

214
00:07:27,713 --> 00:07:28,714
but what I'm not sure of

215
00:07:28,714 --> 00:07:30,216
is how you got from there

216
00:07:30,216 --> 00:07:32,718
to causing a four-car pileup.

217
00:07:32,718 --> 00:07:35,188
DAPHNE: Well, things got
much more difficult

218
00:07:35,188 --> 00:07:38,124
once Simon settled
into the house.

219
00:07:41,928 --> 00:07:43,329
Good evening, Dr. Crane.

220
00:07:43,329 --> 00:07:45,331
I hope you had a pleasant day.

221
00:07:45,331 --> 00:07:47,800
Where's Simon?

222
00:07:49,802 --> 00:07:51,804
I think he's out
with Mr. Crane again.

223
00:07:51,804 --> 00:07:54,307
They seem to have taken quite a shine
to each other.

224
00:07:54,307 --> 00:07:56,309
Simon's introduced him to rugby.

225
00:07:56,742 --> 00:07:58,244
Yes, I really must
thank him for that.

226
00:07:58,244 --> 00:08:01,614
After all, poor Dad, before he came,

227
00:08:01,614 --> 00:08:02,882
had no sport to watch

228
00:08:02,882 --> 00:08:06,385
between the hours
of 2:00 and 6:00 a.m.

229
00:08:08,154 --> 00:08:09,422
Did you happen to see
the kitchen this morning?

230
00:08:09,422 --> 00:08:12,358
Yes. I guess they
got some take-out.

231
00:08:12,358 --> 00:08:16,195
It looked like a kung pao bomb
went off.

232
00:08:16,195 --> 00:08:18,064
I still have moo shu

233
00:08:18,064 --> 00:08:21,067
stuck in the tread
of my driving moccasins.

234
00:08:22,068 --> 00:08:25,404
I'm sorry Simon's been
such an imposition,

235
00:08:25,404 --> 00:08:27,206
but he's leaving soon.

236
00:08:27,206 --> 00:08:29,709
He's decided to tour the
West Coast until the wedding.

237
00:08:29,709 --> 00:08:30,710
Oh, Lord, that's a relief.

238
00:08:30,710 --> 00:08:33,579
Yes... (sighs): Oh...

239
00:08:33,579 --> 00:08:34,947
Oh, by the by,

240
00:08:34,947 --> 00:08:37,450
I invited my friend Holly over
for drinks tonight.

241
00:08:37,950 --> 00:08:39,218
Maybe you could join us.

242
00:08:39,218 --> 00:08:40,520
Might give you two an opportunity

243
00:08:40,520 --> 00:08:42,355
to get better acquainted.

244
00:08:42,355 --> 00:08:44,190
Daphne, if you're offering up
your attractive friend

245
00:08:44,190 --> 00:08:46,959
as some sort of a peace
offering, well, then, I accept.

246
00:08:46,959 --> 00:08:48,194
Perhaps I'd better go

247
00:08:48,194 --> 00:08:50,062
and make myself irresistible.

248
00:08:50,062 --> 00:08:51,130
Well, you won't have time for much.

249
00:08:51,130 --> 00:08:53,533
She's on her way now. Well, it's probably
better that way.

250
00:08:53,533 --> 00:08:55,801
You know, give her a fighting chance.

251
00:08:57,036 --> 00:08:58,804
Mr. Crane,

252
00:08:58,804 --> 00:09:00,072
I thought you were out with Simon.

253
00:09:00,072 --> 00:09:01,541
Nope, just Eddie.

254
00:09:01,541 --> 00:09:02,842
Then where's Simon?

255
00:09:02,842 --> 00:09:04,076
FRASIER: Daphne!

256
00:09:04,076 --> 00:09:06,546
Your brother is in my bed!

257
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:09,549
Nude!

258
00:09:09,549 --> 00:09:12,552
Simon Moon, get out of Dr. Crane's room!

259
00:09:12,552 --> 00:09:13,953
MARTIN: Oh, that poor guy.

260
00:09:13,953 --> 00:09:15,855
He probably just needed a nap.

261
00:09:15,855 --> 00:09:16,856
It's the jet lag.

262
00:09:16,856 --> 00:09:18,691
Couple of days, and he'll be on
our time.

263
00:09:18,691 --> 00:09:20,826
A couple more days,
he'll be on our sidewalk.

264
00:09:20,826 --> 00:09:22,662
Oh, sorry about that.

265
00:09:22,662 --> 00:09:25,031
I'm a bit sleepy today.

266
00:09:25,031 --> 00:09:27,433
I think I'm coming down
with a cold.

267
00:09:27,433 --> 00:09:30,202
(clearing throat and sniffling)

268
